<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10008e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10008e">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10008e"> 8(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> plunder burial mound</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The <mark>plundering of these burial-mounds</mark> - &ldquo;a thing that had never been done before&rdquo; - made a deep impression on the Irish Annalists; it was thought that the Vikings <font color="green">[Olaf and Ivarr, with the Irish prince Lorcan, king of Meath]</font> discovered the existence of the treasure <font color="green">[at New Grange, Knowth and Dowth, on the Boyne]</font> by magic, &ldquo;through paganism and idol worship&rdquo;. <small> A. WALSH, <a name="AWSR" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#AWSR"><cite title="source">Scandinavian Relations with Ireland During the Viking Period</cite></a> (1922) 12n</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
